Determine the Congestion Charge Zone of New York with Prescriptive Analytics¶

What is a congestion charge and why?¶

TheLondon congestion chargeis a fee charged on most motor vehicles operating within the Congestion Charge Zone (CCZ)inCentral Londonbetween 07:00 and 18:00 Mondays to Fridays.

The charge aims to reduce high traffic flow in the central area and raise investment funds for London's transport system.

After ten years since its implementation in 2003, congestion charging scheme resulted in a 10% reduction in traffic volumes from baseline conditions, and an overall reduction of 11% in vehicle.

See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/London_congestion_charge

Business constraints to determine the CCZ blocks:¶

  • Must be located in a business/touristic place (obvious traffic): we choose Manhattan, and will use taxis trips to get the traffic tendancies.

  • The CCZ zone must be homogeneous (composed of contiguous blocks to avoid in/out/in fee penalties)

  • Select the blocks with non linear scoring based on the dropoff/pickup locations (2 blocks with a score of 100 are less than a block with 200) to avoid weird tradeoffs

  • Only trips with less than 3 visitors are candidates to be taxed

  • We cant choose more than x% of the blocks

  • We want to cover a fixed minimum y% amount of the target city

  • We dont want to tax more than z% of the trips.

  • Topological constraints:

    • if 2 neighbor blocks are selected, then you are selected(avoid White/Black/White on horizontal and vertical)
    • you must be selected if all around you are (avoid an White in a square of Black)

What does it mean to apply it to New York?¶

We can use open data: it means handling big data files (taxis trips for each month of 2014 is a 1GB csv file). We will use:

  • pandas to do all the data clean up and split the trips in city block.
  • geospatial open source library to keep the interesting tris in/out of Mahnattan
  • docplex to determine the CCZ area
  • google maps to visualize the solution

Get the taxis trips in New York in 2015 for January from nyctaxitrips.blob.core.windows.net as zipped csv. Unzip it in the temp dir of your machine.

import pyproj

NAD_1983_StatePlane_New_York_Long_Island_FIPS_3104_Feet = "+proj=lcc +lat_1=40.66666666666666 +lat_2=41.03333333333333 +lat_0=40.16666666666666 +lon_0=-74 +x_0=300000.00000000 +y_0=0 +ellps=GRS80 +datum=NAD83 +to_meter=0.3048006096012192 +no_defs"

map_prj = pyproj.Proj(NAD_1983_StatePlane_New_York_Long_Island_FIPS_3104_Feet, preserve_units=True)
wgs84 = pyproj.Proj("+proj=longlat +ellps=WGS84 +datum=WGS84 +no_def")

class Poly:
    def __init__(self):
        self.bbox = None
        self.rings = [] # list of polys !
    def populate(self, m, src_proj, target_proj): # m is a shape record
        print m.shape
        maxcount = len(m.shape.parts)-1
        for i,lb in enumerate(m.shape.parts):
            ub = (m.shape.parts[i+1]-1) if i<maxcount else None
            ring = list(m.shape.points[lb:ub])
            sarea = shapefile.signed_area(ring)
            # exclude holes
            if sarea <0:
                projected = [pyproj.transform(src_proj, target_proj, po[0],po[1]) for po in ring]
                self.rings.append(projected)
        # once projected, compute bbox
        (minx,miny) = self.rings[0][0]
        (maxx,maxy) = (minx,miny)
        for ring in self.rings:
            for (x,y) in ring:
                if x < minx:
                    minx = x
                if x > maxx:
                    maxx = x
                if y < miny:
                    miny = y
                if y > maxy:
                    maxy = y
        self.bbox= [minx, miny, maxx, maxy]
        
    def point_inside_ring(self,x,y,poly):
        n = len(poly)
        inside =False
        p1x,p1y = poly[0]
        for i in range(n+1):
            p2x,p2y = poly[i % n]
            if y > min(p1y,p2y):
                if y <= max(p1y,p2y):
                    if x <= max(p1x,p2x):
                        if p1y != p2y:
                            xinters = (y-p1y)*(p2x-p1x)/(p2y-p1y)+p1x
                        if p1x == p2x or x <= xinters:
                            inside = not inside
            p1x,p1y = p2x,p2y
        return inside

    def contains(self,x,y):
        bbox = self.bbox
        if x < bbox[0] or x > bbox[2] or y < bbox[1] or y > bbox[3]:
            return False
        for ring in self.rings:
            if self.point_inside_ring(x,y, ring):
                return True
        return False

In [171]:
from PIL import Image, ImageDraw

MASK_SIZE = (1000,1000)

class Intersector:
    def __init__(self, polys):
        self.polys = polys # list of polygons !
        self.masks = []
        self.create_masks()
        
    def icoord(self, bb, c):
        (x,y) = c
        (w,h) = MASK_SIZE
        minx = bb[0]
        miny = bb[1]
        maxx = bb[2]
        maxy = bb[3]
        dx = maxx - minx
        dy = maxy - miny

        i = round(w * ((x - minx)/dx))
        j = round(h * ((y - miny)/dy))
        
        if i<0:
            i=0
        if j<0:
            j=0
        if i>=w:
            i=w
        if j>=h:
            j=h
        return (i,j)
    
    def simplify(self, pp):
        n = []
        last = None
        for p in pp:
            if last is None:
                last = p
                n.append(p)
            else:
                if p != last:
                    last = p
                    n.append(p)
        return n
        
    def create_masks(self):
        for poly in self.polys:
            bb = poly.bbox
            im = Image.new('L', MASK_SIZE, 0)
            (w,h) = MASK_SIZE
            for ring in poly.rings:
                pp = [self.icoord(bb, point) for point in ring]
                pp = self.simplify(pp)
                # draw that in im
                draw = ImageDraw.Draw(im)
                draw.polygon(pp,fill=0xffffff,outline=0xffffff)
            self.masks.append(im)
            #im.show()
            

    def keep_point(self,x,y, fast=True):
        if fast:
            # fast mode using bitmap
            for imask, mask in enumerate(self.masks):
                pol = self.polys[imask]
                (x,y) = self.icoord(pol.bbox, (x,y))
                (w,h) = MASK_SIZE
                if  (x>=0) and (x<w) and (y>=0) and (y<h):
                    if mask.getpixel((x,y)) != 0:
                        return True
        else:
            # slow geometric mode
            for poly in self.polys:
                if poly.contains(x,y):
                    return True
        return False

    i, j, score = hit_row
    assert i in xrange
    assert j in yrange
    assert score >= 0
    if score:
        # store the average score.
        hit_map[i, j] = score / avg_score

def total_score_normalized(mdl):
    return total_score / avg_score

def get_score(mdl, i, j):
    """
    Returns the score of grid cell (i,j), 0 if cell is not in hit map
    :param i:
    :param j:
    """
    return hit_map.get((i, j), 0)
In [192]:
def post_implied_and(mdl, mid_var, var1, var2, ctname=None):
    mdl.add_constraint(1 + mid_var >= var1 + var2, ctname)

cell_vars = mdl.binary_var_matrix(xrange, yrange, name="toll")

We state that (i,j) is tolled whenever its two immediate horizontal neighbors are

In other terms it defines a logical OR

            ctname = 'horiz_%d_%d' % (i, j)
            post_implied_and(mdl, cell_vars[i, j], cell_vars[ileft, j], cell_vars[iright, j], ctname)

Avoid isolated cells

If all neighbors (8) are unselected, then the cell is 0

In [197]:
for i in range(1, xmax-1):
    for j in range(1, ymax-1):
        this_cell_var = cell_vars[i,j]
        if this_cell_var.ub == 0:
            pass
        else:
            neighbors = cell_vars[i-1,j+1] + cell_vars[i,j+1] + cell_vars[i+1,j+1] + cell_vars[i-1, j] + cell_vars[i+1,j] + cell_vars[i-1,j-1] + cell_vars[i,j-1]+ cell_vars[i+1,j-1]
            mdl.add_constraint(this_cell_var <= neighbors)

total_setup_cost = setup_cost * mdl.sum(cell_vars)
mdl.add_kpi(total_setup_cost, "Total Setup Cost")

# we want to cover as much hits as possible
# we use square normalized score to avoid tradeoffs
square_normalized_scores = [(lambda k: k * k)(get_score(mdl, i, j)) for i in xrange for j in yrange]
all_cell_vars = [cell_vars[i, j] for i in xrange for j in yrange]
total_hit_square_coverage = mdl.scal_prod(all_cell_vars, square_normalized_scores)
total_hit_coverage = mdl.scal_prod(all_cell_vars, [get_score(mdl, i, j) for i in xrange for j in yrange] )
mdl.add_kpi(total_hit_coverage, "Total Hit Coverage")

mdl.maximize(total_hit_square_coverage - total_setup_cost)
